<PubmedArticleSet>
<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">30372656</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2019</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>23</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2019</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>23</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1466-447X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>37</Volume><Issue>8</Issue><PubDate><Year>2019</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of sports sciences</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Sports Sci</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Prevalence of sleep disorders and sleep problems in an elite super rugby union team.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>950</StartPage><EndPage>957</EndPage><MedlinePgn>950-957</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1080/02640414.2018.1537092</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The aim of this study was to determine the prevalence of sleep disorders in an elite rugby union team using in-laboratory polysomnography (PSG) and sleep questionnaires. Twenty-five elite rugby union players underwent a night of PSG during the "off-season" of the Super Rugby competition to assess their sleep. Of interest were measurements that detected the presence of obstructive sleep apnea (OSA; apnea-hypopnea index &#x2265;5 events/hr) and the presence of moderate-severe periodic leg movements during sleep (PLMs; &#x2265;15 events/hr). Players completed sleep-related questionnaires to assess daytime sleepiness, perception of insomnia, risk of OSA, and the presence of restless legs syndrome (RLS) and underwent basic anthropometric assessments including body mass index and neck circumference. OSA was present in 24% (n=6) of players and PLMs &#x2265;15 events/hr in 12% (n=3). Questionnaire responses showed that all players had insomnia defined subthreshold insomnia and excessive daytime sleepiness, two players were identified as being at risk for OSA and none were classified as having RLS. In conclusion, sleep disorders and excessive sleepiness are common in elite rugby union players. A process to identify and manage sleep disorders should be considered by teams to optimise their physical recovery, athletic performance and to safeguard their health.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Dunican</LastName><ForeName>Ian C</ForeName><Initials>IC</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a Centre for Sleep Science, School of Human Sciences , The University of Western Australia , Crawley , WA , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Walsh</LastName><ForeName>Jennifer</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a Centre for Sleep Science, School of Human Sciences , The University of Western Australia , Crawley , WA , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Higgins</LastName><ForeName>Charles C</ForeName><Initials>CC</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>b Western Force , Rugby Western Australia , Floreat , WA , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jones</LastName><ForeName>Maddison J</ForeName><Initials>MJ</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>c School of Human Sciences , The University of Western Australia , Crawley , WA , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Maddison</LastName><ForeName>Kathleen</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a Centre for Sleep Science, School of Human Sciences , The University of Western Australia , Crawley , WA , Australia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Caldwell</LastName><ForeName>John A</ForeName><Initials>JA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>d Coastal Performance Consulting , Australia , FL , USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>David</LastName><ForeName>Hillma